1
00:00:01,040 --> 00:00:04,500
Let's test our coil, so to speak, for fitness for duty.

2
00:00:05,680 --> 00:00:11,740
So, we have a digital signal generator, an oscilloscope, and an ammeter.

3
00:00:12,640 --> 00:00:25,820
For the DC ammeter to register the high-frequency AC signal, we put in a fast diode, we'll cut off one half-cycle.

4
00:00:26,700 --> 00:00:31,560
We can't count on accuracy, so we'll track by divisions.

5
00:00:32,940 --> 00:00:33,960
So, let's watch.

6
00:00:35,500 --> 00:00:45,280
This system of ours is not a step-down transformer, since the number of turns and wire here is more than on the inductor.

7
00:00:46,080 --> 00:00:54,940
Accordingly, we send a half-volt amplitude sine wave signal from the signal generator.

8
00:00:56,320 --> 00:01:01,160
This is the blue trace, yellow, accordingly, on the grenade.

9
00:01:02,380 --> 00:01:06,140
On these capacitors here, the ones in parallel.

10
00:01:07,560 --> 00:01:11,260
It turns out we see that our voltage amplitude is higher.

11
00:01:11,540 --> 00:01:12,240
Everything's normal.

12
00:01:14,200 --> 00:01:16,040
The transformer is not step-down.

13
00:01:16,040 --> 00:01:20,420
So, now we measure the current that the signal generator delivers.

14
00:01:22,500 --> 00:01:29,200
We connect our ammeter, disconnect.

15
00:01:29,400 --> 00:01:32,220
There, the signal probe from the generator went to the ammeter.

16
00:01:33,080 --> 00:01:40,620
We see the current matches 13 divisions.

17
00:01:42,160 --> 00:01:48,000
OK, now we measure the current that will be in the same mode on the grenade.

18
00:01:49,040 --> 00:02:01,480
We hook up to the output of the grenade, put the signal probe in place and lock it in.

19
00:02:03,020 --> 00:02:10,760
The current at the grenade output is 21 divisions for us.

20
00:02:15,520 --> 00:02:17,200
The picture is the same.

21
00:02:18,180 --> 00:02:27,780
Which means we're recording the moment when the current at the output of this coil exceeds the input current.

22
00:02:27,880 --> 00:02:31,300
And on top of that we have a voltage gain.

23
00:02:31,920 --> 00:02:36,280
Now the tuning accuracy.

24
00:02:36,660 --> 00:02:38,600
Why do many people miss?

25
00:02:39,120 --> 00:02:40,400
Here's our frequency.

26
00:02:41,420 --> 00:02:46,300
For example, let's nudge it, say, 300 Hz.

27
00:02:47,320 --> 00:02:52,820
We see our current has already dropped, and the amplitude there is falling.

28
00:02:53,500 --> 00:03:07,280
Let's nudge the frequency a bit more and we see, there goes the voltage gain, and the current is much less than what's coming from the generator.

29
00:03:07,840 --> 00:03:10,080
That's why the tuning has to be precise.

30
00:03:14,180 --> 00:03:17,320
The same thing happens if we add frequency.

31
00:03:18,280 --> 00:03:19,620
For example, we'll overshoot.

32
00:03:28,300 --> 00:03:29,700
The current is also small.

33
00:03:31,180 --> 00:03:38,620
Let's return the frequency to the one we need, the one this coil will operate at.

34
00:03:39,420 --> 00:03:48,100
And we'll see that the trace divisions are the same, the voltage gain is also there.
